DSAN Competation

1 Introduction

The period between 2022 and 2023 may pose challenges for new graduates seeking positions in the technology industry, as many large companies are conducting massive layoffs of software developers, data analysts, and data scientists. It is therefore crucial for our DSAN students to have an overview of the current job market and available openings, in order to gain insight into the current landscape of data-related jobs.

2 Data Description

  • This dataset is the outcome of a web-crawling exercise aimed at identifying employment opportunities that could potentially interest DSAN students.
  • There are roughly 85 searches, each yielding up to 10 job postings, for a total of around 850 jobs, which are currently active online, as of 04/14/2023 .
  • The postings were obtained using the following search query terms:
    • [âdata scientistâ,âdata analystâ,âneural networksâ,âbig data and cloud computingâ,âmachine learningâ, âreinforcement learningâ,âdeep learningâ, âtime seriesâ,âblock chainâ,ânatural language processingâ]
  • The searches are divided into two categories: nationwide and local searches for the United States as a whole and DC, respectively. It is worth noting that these searches are not mutually exclusive, and the files may contain duplicate job postings. These duplicates should be removed during the cleaning process.
  • Furthermore, the DC search result extend outside of the specified search area. However, they likely contain a higher sampling of jobs in the DC area.
  • The search results are stored in multiple JSON files, with the file name representing the search term. with each file containing the results of a single search

3 Data Visualization

3.1 An General Overview

  • The Top 10 Hiring Companies
  • The distribution of Job Categories

From the plot, it is evident that the majority of hiring in the data-related job market is centered around natural language processing, deep learning, big data, and cloud computing, with time series-related work being the least prominent. This trend is likely due to the wave of popularity in large language models like ChatGPT and Barn, which require advanced expertise in natural language processing and deep learning.

Regarding companies, Upwork leads the board with 56 current openings, followed by Booz Allen Hamilton with 17 and Apple with 15 openings. The lack of other familiar names indicates the severity of tech layoffs in the data-related job market. However, it is important to note that there may be smaller or newer companies offering data-related positions that are not reflected in this dataset.

3.2 How are these companies paying and which categories their job belong to

The Sankey plot reveals that the majority of job postings from the top five companies (Upwarok, Apple, Booz Allen Hamilton, Deloitte and Walmart) opt to withhold salary details. A significant portion of these undisclosed roles are related to Neural Networks. Moreover, the chart highlights that Blockchain-related roles command higher compensation, a trend that aligns with industry expectations.

3.3 Most Job Listed by Location

As of 04/14/2023, the majority of available data-related jobs on the market are not location-specific, with 236 jobs available for remote work. California comes in second with 131 available jobs. It is important to note this trend towards remote work as it offers more flexibility for job seekers, especially during times of economic uncertainty.

3.4 Which Job Recurring Platform to Choose

  • Top 5 Job Posting Platform
  • The change of Frequency in Job posting

The plot indicates that LinkedIn (66 posts) remains the most popular job posting platform for companies actively looking to hire, followed by ZipRecruiter (60) and Upwork (56). Therefore, our DSAN students should consider these platforms when looking for a job in the data-related field.

In terms of frequency of job listings, AngelList tops the chart with 34 listings on a single day. However, this is more likely due to filling in NaN values, and LinkedIn remains the leader in terms of the frequency of job listings. As a result, LinkedIn remains the go-to platform for students seeking data-related jobs.
